LETTERS TO ATTICUS VII. 23-25

For your query as to the state of affairs in this quarter, Capua and the levy are in stagnation: our cause is despaired of: every one is in flight, unless some god help Pompey to join that army of Domitius with his own. It would seem that we shall know all in a day or so. As requested I send you a copy of Caesar’s letter. Many of my correspondents say that he is quite satisfied with me. Ι can allow that, provided I continue to do nothing to stain my honour.
